{'chunks': [{'text': '=+=+=+=+=+=+=+=+=\ntitle: Lothair II\ntext: Lothair II (835 –) was the king of Lotharingia from 855 until his death. He was the second son of Emperor Lothair I and Ermengarde of Tours. He was married to Teutberga (died 875), daughter of Boso the Elder.\n=+=+=+=+=+=+=+=+=\ntitle: Ermengarde of Tours\ntext: Ermengarde of Tours (d. 20 March 851) was the daughter of Hugh of Tours, a member of the Etichonen family. In October 821 in Thionville, she married the Carolingian Emperor Lothair I of the Franks (795–855). In 849, two years before her death, she made a donation to the abbey Erstein in the Elsass, in which she is buried. Lothair and Ermengarde had eight children:', 'uri': 'benchmark/2wiki/2wiki_corpus_100.txt', 'filename': '2wiki_corpus_100.txt', 'private': False, 'uploaded_at': None, 'document_key': 'chunk-6f0a4ec951ffa0d7c60695104c565cb0', '_relevance_score': 0.79296875}, {'text': "title: Teutberga\ntext: Teutberga( died 11 November 875) was a queen of Lotharingia by marriage to Lothair II. She was a daughter of Bosonid Boso the Elder and sister of Hucbert, the lay- abbot of St. Maurice's Abbey.\n=+=+=+=+=+=+=+=+=\ntitle: Theodred II (Bishop of Elmham)\ntext: Theodred II was a medieval Bishop of Elmham. The date of Theodred's consecration unknown, but the date of his death was sometime between 995 and 997.\n=+=+=+=+=+=+=+=+=\ntitle: Lambert, Margrave of Tuscany\ntext: Lambert( died after 938) was the second son of Adalbert II of Tuscany and Bertha, daughter of Lothair II of Lotharingia. He succeeded his elder brother, Guy, as count and duke of Lucca and margrave of Tuscany on his death in 928 or 929 without heirs. In 931, before 17 October, Hugh, King of Italy, disowned and removed Lambert, giving Tuscany and the familial possession of Lucca to his brother Boso. Hugh was Guy and Lambert's half- brother, as they had the same mother. When Guy died, Hugh married Guy's widow, Marozia.", 'uri': 'benchmark/2wiki/2wiki_corpus_100.txt', 'filename': '2wiki_corpus_100.txt', 'private': False, 'uploaded_at': None, 'document_key': 'chunk-1f91bfd918df15f1bc5fee82a634df24', '_relevance_score': 0.6796875}, {'text': '=+=+=+=+=+=+=+=+=\ntitle: Bertha, daughter of Lothair II\ntext: Bertha( 863- 8 – March 925 in Lucca) was countess of Arles by marriage to Theobald of Arles, and margravine of Tuccany by marriage to Adalbert II of Tuscany. She served as regent of Lucca and Tuscany from 915 until 916 during the minority of her son Guy of Tuscany. She was described as beautiful, spirited, and courageous, and her influence over her spouse was, coupled with ambition, attributed to have involved her husbands in many wars. She was the second illegitimate daughter of Lothair II, King of Lotharingia, by his concubine Waldrada.\n=+=+=+=+=+=+=+=+=\ntitle: Adolf I of Lotharingia\ntext: Adolf I of Lotharingia, count of Keldachgau, Vogt of Deutz from 1008 until 1018, was the son of Hermann I" Pusillus"( the Little Pfalzgraf), count palatine of Lotharingia. He left three sons:\n=+=+=+=+=+=+=+=+=\ntitle: Waldrada of Lotharingia\ntext: Waldrada was the mistress, and later the wife, of Lothair II of Lotharingia.', 'uri': 'benchmark/2wiki/2wiki_corpus_100.txt', 'filename': '2wiki_corpus_100.txt', 'private': False, 'uploaded_at': None, 'document_key': 'chunk-4fa26b2f1061b735530fc3d080a65ded', '_relevance_score': 0.6171875}, {'text': '=+=+=+=+=+=+=+=+=\ntitle: Waldrada of Lotharingia\ntext: Waldrada was the mistress, and later the wife, of Lothair II of Lotharingia.\n=+=+=+=+=+=+=+=+=\ntitle: Theobald of Arles\ntext: Theobald( c. 854-895), count of Arles, was a Frank from the Bosonid- family. He was a son of Hucbert and married Bertha, an illegitimate daughter of Lothair II, King of Lotharingia, who was renowned for her beauty and spirit. They had two sons Hugh of Italy and Boso of Tuscany.\n=+=+=+=+=+=+=+=+=\ntitle: The Wonderful World of Captain Kuhio\ntext: The film was released in Japan on 10 October 2009.\n=+=+=+=+=+=+=+=+=\ntitle: Coney Island Baby (film)\ntext: Coney Island Baby is a 2003 comedy- drama in which film producer Amy Hobby made her directorial debut. Karl Geary wrote the film and Tanya Ryno was the film\'s producer. The music was composed by Ryan Shore. The film was shot in Sligo, Ireland, which is known locally as" Coney Island". The film was screened at the Newport International Film Festival. Hobby won the Jury Award for" Best First Time Director". The film made its premiere television broadcast on the Sundance Channel.', 'uri': 'benchmark/2wiki/2wiki_corpus_100.txt', 'filename': '2wiki_corpus_100.txt', 'private': False, 'uploaded_at': None, 'document_key': 'chunk-9549ccd9e8ff759c531183f83ba2d19f', '_relevance_score': 0.494140625}, {'text': '=+=+=+=+=+=+=+=+=\ntitle: Edith Carlmar\ntext: Edith Carlmar (Edith Mary Johanne Mathiesen) (15 November 1911 – 17 May 2003) was an Norwagian actress and Norway\'s first female film director. She is known for films such as "Fjols til fjells" (1957), "Aldri annet enn bråk" (1954), and "Ung flukt" (1959). Her 1949 film, "Døden er et kjærtegnDeath is a Caress"), is considered to be Norway\'s first film noir. The last film she directed, "Ung Flukt", introduced Liv Ullmann, Norway\'s most famous actor internationally, to the silver screen. Carlmar came from a poor family in the working class districts of East Oslo. However, she did manage to take dancing classes and made her debut on stage at the age of 15. In the theater she met Otto Carlmar whom she married three years later. From 1936 she worked as an actress in various theatres. Here she met the film director Tancred Ibsen who introduced her to the world of cinema. In 1949 she and her husband started Carlmar Film A/S, and began writing scripts, directing and producing films. They made ten feature films over a ten-year period. After a decade of film-making Carlmar retired as a director. In the last part of her life she accepted only minor', 'uri': 'benchmark/2wiki/2wiki_corpus_100.txt', 'filename': '2wiki_corpus_100.txt', 'private': False, 'uploaded_at': None, 'document_key': 'chunk-30fd97885ea5a20d234ddf6b018dc747', '_relevance_score': 0.318359375}], 'entities': [{'text': 'WALDRADA', 'document_key': 'ent-60a8981206f2c09ffffc21d9483654a5', 'entity_type': 'PERSON', 'description': ['Waldrada was the mistress, and later wife, of Lothair II, implicated in the royal lineage and political intrigue of the time.', 'Waldrada was the mistress and later the wife of Lothair II of Lotharingia, a notable figure in the historical context of the region.'], '_relevance_score': 0.6328125}, {'text': 'LOTHAIR II', 'document_key': 'ent-8ce95c5eafa36a16c61a0a0d3e2b9109', 'entity_type': 'PERSON', 'description': ['Lothair II was the king to whom Teutberga was married, playing a significant role in the political landscape of Lotharingia.', 'Lothair II was the king of Lotharingia from 855 until his death, and the second son of Emperor Lothair I and Ermengarde of Tours.', 'Lothair II was the King of Lotharingia and father of Bertha, known for his relationships and political maneuvers during his reign.', 'Lothair II was a king of Lotharingia, significant for his relationships and rule during his time.'], '_relevance_score': 0.62109375}, {'text': 'TEUTBERGA', 'document_key': 'ent-1e0fa5983b0912337e26b092da95f0c4', 'entity_type': 'PERSON', 'description': ['Teutberga was a queen of Lotharingia by marriage to Lothair II, known for being the daughter of Bosonid Boso the Elder and having ties to important historical figures.', 'Teutberga was the wife of Lothair II and the daughter of Boso the Elder, associated with the royal lineage of Lotharingia.'], '_relevance_score': 0.53515625}, {'text': 'ERMENGARDE OF TOURS', 'document_key': 'ent-bca3734e55c2b7eab4efc5e89de6888e', 'entity_type': 'PERSON', 'description': ['Ermengarde of Tours was the daughter of Hugh of Tours, married to Emperor Lothair I, and made a donation to the abbey Erstein where she is buried.'], '_relevance_score': 0.515625}, {